Additional details

TCL Q6 Class Smart TVs combine premium picture technology with outstanding value for endless entertainment. QLED Quantum Dot technology and HDR PRO+ with Dolby Vision you can enjoy enhanced contrast, accurate colors and fine details utilizing all the most advanced HDR formats with Motion Rate 240 with MEMC frame insertion for exceptional motion clarity. TCL’s High Brightness+ Direct LED Backlight produces brighter images for an enhanced viewing experience for all your favorite movies and TV shows. Now featuring the TCL AIPQ Processor that optimizes each scene for an unrivaled cinematic experience. Beyond movies and TV shows, you can get in the game with Game Accelerator 120* together with Auto Game Mode for the lowest latency for a more responsive gameplay without lag, designed to keep you at the top of any leaderboard. Including Dolby Atmos, DTS Virtual:X, and a new Enhanced Dialogue Mode, TCL Q6 TVs provide a complete audio package. TCL Q Class Smart TVs: Compelling Color and Choice.

      Reviewed in the United States on March 21, 2025
      Size: 65 inchesStyle: TV only
      Short version: I love our new TCL TV! Long version: I was worried that a $375 TV would leave me with some buyer's remorse, but nope! I'm quite pleased with it. My only complaint is that the Google TV startup was slow. Fortunately there's a setting,... See more
      Short version: I love our new TCL TV!

      Long version: I was worried that a $375 TV would leave me with some buyer's remorse, but nope! I'm quite pleased with it. My only complaint is that the Google TV startup was slow. Fortunately there's a setting, easily accessible via the "settings" gear on the remote, to have the TV start up with whatever input it last used, and that speeds the TV power-on cycle significantly.

      Speaking of settings, it's delightful to finally have a TV that gives me proper control over the picture without needing to install an app on my phone. The HDMI Audio Return Channel worked straightaway, no issues, but we did have to make sure that our sound system was plugged into HDMI 3.

      We're not using the built-in apps on the TCL. We have an external ROKU and a PC plugged into HDMI 1 and 2, so we already have what we need without those apps.

      In summary: assuming it doesn't suddenly burn out or explode or otherwise cease to work, it's a *fantastic* deal for $375. It's still day one, so that jury won't return for a while.

      It's possible that I'm just happy to not be dealing with our old Vizio TV anymore.

    • Anonymous
      4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Great TV, But Has Some Flaws
      Reviewed in the United States on January 4, 2025
      Size: 43 inchesStyle: TV only
      It’s mostly a great TV, but…. The Google TV on this TV has glitches and problems that review sites and individual reviewers never mention, because they don’t scrutinize it enough and they don’t check over time to see if everything works. For example, some of the... See more
      It’s mostly a great TV, but….

      The Google TV on this TV has glitches and problems that review sites and individual reviewers never mention, because they don’t scrutinize it enough and they don’t check over time to see if everything works. For example, some of the apps keep freezing – CNN on the MAX app freezes EVERY TIME it goes to a commercial in the morning, and you have to exit CNN and re-enter CNN to fix it. I tried clearing the cache for the MAX app, and restarting Google TV – didn’t help. I’ve had similar problems with certain other apps – PlutoTV does this sometimes when streaming a channel, and you have to exit it and re-enter it, as does the Roku Channel. Antenna TV, the TCL channels, Netflix, and many other apps seem to work flawlessly, but we should be able to use ANY app we choose at any time during the day without problems.

      Other problems with Google TV:
      It takes 60-90 seconds to warm up after you turn on the TV. If you press buttons before then, it will respond so slowly with such long delays, like 10 seconds after each press, that you’ll be infuriated.
      Google TV has its own channels which is an aggregate of many other services like Pluto, Xumo, etc, but it has flaws. For one, some of the channels in the guide are mislabeled, says “ABC” but clicking on it goes to some other channel. For another, every time you use a channel through Google TV, the TV will never again go to screen saver or automatic shut off until you turn off the TV yourself and turn it back on.

      One positive thing about the TV is it has the most crystal clear, perfect picture on the Smart HDR picture setting. It did not when I got the TV, but this “AIPQ deep learning AI processor” thing seems to have learned after the first day to adjust the settings perfectly, you just have to make a few minor adjustments and wait about 24 hours.

      So mostly it’s a good TV, good remote, and most apps work OK, but it has some ridiculous problems like I described above and there’s no solution to it.
